As Ben Jones wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/18/2004 at 05:42:34 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>Hi,
>
>I'm trying to prove (or disprove) the following:
>
>  (n ^ (x mod (p-1))) mod p === (n ^ x) mod p
>
>where p is prime and n is relatively prime to p. (I'm using the
>"computing style" mod operator here, rather than the math one. Hope
>that's OK, because I'm a computer programmer, not a mathematician! :))
>
>[Difficulty]
>I guess I'm just not confident enough with shuffling these "mod"
>operators around. Also, in the specific case where this has cropped
>up, n is in fact a primitive root of p, and x is always prime (and, x
>is always relatively prime to (p-1)!). I can't decide if this is
>significant or not, which makes it harder to think about, if you see
>what I mean.
>
>[Thoughts]
>Intuitively, I think the proposition is true by Fermat's Little
>Theorem. If I express x as being q*(p-1)+r (where q is the integer
>part of x/(p-1) and r is the remainder), then:
>
>  (n^x) mod p = n ^ (q*(p-1)+r)  mod p
>              = (n ^ (q*(p-1))) * (n^r)  mod p
>              = (n ^ (p-1))^q * (n^r) mod p
>
>Then by F.L.T, as (n,p) = 1:
>
>              = (1^q * (n^r) mod p 
>              = (n^r)) mod p
>              = (n^(x mod (p-1))) mod p
>
>Is this argument sound? I can never quite be sure with all these mods
>floating around. Are there any necessary conditions that I've missed?
>
>I tested this emperically for a few values and it seemed to work, but
>I don't feel I have a rigorous proof and without that I can't accept
>the result. 
>
>Many thanks in advance for your help!

Hi Ben,

